    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="749"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d749">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.61/972: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-18">January 18,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received January 19—1:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>176. Stettinius’<note n="22" xml:id="d749fn1">Edward R. Stettinius, Jr., Under
                        Secretary of State.</note> radio statement regarding United States
                    cooperation with Soviet Union receives 3½ inches of prominently placed space in
                    Moscow newspapers for January 18.<note n="23" xml:id="d749fn2">These remarks
                        were made during the second broadcast of the National Broadcasting Company
                        series, “The State Department Speaks”; see Department of State <hi
                            rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, January 15, 1944, p. 74.</note> Reporting
                    Under Secretary’s statement that any other policy would be a tragic mistake,
                    item quotes his remarks regarding impression of Soviet peoples resourcefulness
                    and courage derived from contacts with Soviet representatives in America, and
                    statement America has much to gain and nothing to lose by continuing close
                    collaboration with Soviet Union now and after war.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
